21/21 Now is the time to realize that the blockchain‚Äôs future will depend on how well we expose its capabilities universally & openly.
20/21 Will the sum of blockchain technologies turn into a giant Internet, or will their journey unfold as a messy and fragmented evolution?
19/21 We can‚Äôt force blockchain standards on the market, but the market needs to embrace standards over time.
18/21 In 2017, we need to see serious discussions on universal standards, and real intentions from industry participants to work together.
17/21 There are promising examples of blockchain related standards & we need to see more of them, e.g. IPFS for files and ERC20 for tokens.
16/21 We need universal tools that no one owns, but that benefit everybody, similar to the Web technologies that liberated the Internet.
15/21 A trust services layer could be that API veneer that homogenizes how we create, move, check, inspect, follow historical paths, etc.
14/21 Blockchain browsers (B-Browsers) are going to be important, and we will start to see them in 2017.
13/21 Blockchains could have a number of standards above the Internet‚Äôs existing ones, allowing smooth bridging from one layer to another.
12/21 The Internet and the Web have their standards. Where are the blockchain equivalent?
11/21 Many areas ripe for standards: smart contracts, tokens, security, storage, messaging, identities, naming, record-keeping & more.
10/21 In order to grow-up, blockchains will eventually need a lot of standards that are vendor and solutions agnostic.
9/21 The state of collaboration between blockchains is plagued by timid efforts for building bridges and lateral co-operative capabilities.
8/21 An engineer that knows how to program Bitcoin needs to relearn what they know, in order to develop on other blockchains.
7/21 Unfortunately, blockchains don‚Äôt have that luxury yet, as each platform has its own set of technologies and methods to work with.
6/21 Since early days, the Internet and Web have matured nicely, and today rely on close to 200 standards across several layers.
5/21 This scenario is not unlike the position the Internet was in, prior to the Web.
4/21 With so much homogeneity in functionality intent, why so many different and incompatible blockchain technologies and software?
3/21 The variety of available blockchains handle same few basic functions, recording (digital) value without needing a 3rd party to move it.
2/21 What if blockchain tech is more like the Internet & we are still waiting for its Web layers, to fully exploit its capabilities?
1/21 Maybe The Blockchain is Still Waiting for its Web. Here is Why in 20 points.

6/6 For one slide to show it all, (Re)-Explaining the Blockchain in One Slide https://t.co/wopbQv4hAd https://t.co/uGfkyToiNK
5/6 Blockchain as MARKETPLACE: a) creating new economies, b) work/reward system, c) sandbox for money + business.
4/6 Blockchain as a TRUST SERVICES LAYER: a) record keeping, verifications, proofs, b) custody, rights, titles, c) identity & naming.
3/6 Blockchain as UTILITY: a) creating/moving value (assets), b) storing value (cryptocurrency), c) processing transactions and logic.
2/6 Blockchain for DEVELOPMENT: a) new software develop. environment, b) programming money/value, c) dealing with ledgers vs. databases.
1/6 9 Ways to think about what the blockchain enables, along 4 segments: 1/ Software Develop., 2/ Utility, 3/ Trust Layer, 4/ Marketplace.

14/14 The blockchain is destined to become the new website. Read More: https://t.co/2AvWZqjG5g
13/14 Advice: Pair a technical person with a business manager: magical moments happen when business and technology understand each other.
12/14 Advice: Acquire knowledge internally. Don‚Äôt outsource it, because you would be outsourcing experience you need to gain directly.
11/14 Things to learn: writing smart contracts, creating or tokenizing assets, interacting with blockchain APIs, programming a blockchain.
10/14 Moving assets, identities, ownerships, contracts, balances, records, data on the blockchain is 1st phase like 1st websites in 90‚Äôs.
9/14 That would create a large inventory of tradeable blockchain assets, and a resulting groundswell of economic activity.
8/14 Imagine if any real world asset could be mirrored on the blockchain directly (creation/transfer), or indirectly (anchoring).
7/14 Think about other familiar asset classes that can mimic Bitcoin‚Äôs capabilities, and you can start to imagine some of the possibilities.
6/14 Bitcoin as cryptocurrency is quintessential digital asset & moves efficiently & transparently across global blockchain w no boundaries.
5/14 With blockchain, asset ownership is with owner of the asset, not with a (central) party who owns a database that points to the owner.
4/14 Exchanging anything we own, and challenging existing trusted authorities and custodians that held the keys to accessing our assets.
3/14 "Decentralization of Trust" enables new "value flow without intermediaries", unleashes new opportunities.
2/14 5 phases of Internet: Personal Communications, Self-Publishing, E-Commerce, Social Web, Trust-based Services.
1/14 Every company will have a blockchain, or be on a blockchain or several, just as organizations are involved in many websites today.

11/11 Read more on Maximizing User Adoption by Understanding Behavioral Economics for Startups https://t.co/WJDE5Ipfdy
10/11 Find your risk seeking segments of users (and there could be several of them), and you will get easier adoptions for your product.
9/11 Understanding prospect theory is critical in finding your initial target segments, so you don‚Äôt spin your wheels with the wrong ones.
8/11 On your website & communications, highlight loss words & remind prospects wht they are ‚Äúmissing out‚Äù v. wht they could be gaining.
7/11 Break-up the different parts of your product & ask yourself: is this feature in the domain of risk aversion or risk seeking?
6/11 Risk averse prospects are happy with their current situation and will push-back on your pitches and trials.
5/11 Startups need to go after a segment of prospects that are risk-seekers: currently with no solution, or incurring losses.
4/11 People strongly prefer avoiding losses to acquiring gains. Losses are twice as powerful as gains for moving people from status quo.
3/11 People make decisions based on the potential value of losses and gains rather than the final outcome.
2/11 Prospect theory is behavioral economic theory describing how people choose b/w alternatives that involve risk, with known outcomes.
1/11 It's important to understand that ‚ÄúPeople tend to be risk-seeking in the domain of losses and risk-averse in the domain of gains‚Äù.

10/10 Read more, Is the Blockchain an Alphabet Soup or a Full-Stack? - https://t.co/auFINAhR1m
9/10 There is case for blockchain based on a-la-carte alphabet soup menu but there is also case for more benefits from full-stack adherence.
8/10 The more stack layers you remove, the more need to be realistic about benefits expectations derived from a blockchain adoption.
7/10 The more pure, the more benefits in terms of innovation, disruption and reengineering potential.
6/10 How much functionality you remove is a consideration when assessing the potential benefits one can derive from that blockchain.
5/10 List of variations is long: blockchain no Btc, Btc no keys, ledgers no mining, consensus no Btc, ledgers no tokens or no mining, etc.
4/10 Are we at the dawn of a new alphabet soup of technologies, or a fully organized stack? And what is the better approach?
3/10 While seeing various degrees of implementations, need to understand what we give-up when pieces of the ‚Äústack‚Äù intentionally missing.
2/10 Need to understand various nuances in benefits and drawbacks of having a ‚Äúfull-stack‚Äù blockchain versus ‚Äúnon full-stack‚Äù one.
1/10 Blockchain maximalism takes a purist view and follows a Blockchain ‚Äúfull-stack‚Äù approach, advocating it‚Äôs an all-or-none situation.

4/13 If you use ‚Äúblockchains without Bitcoin‚Äù just to avoid public blockchains, you will be subjected to a huge market blind spot. Do both.

6/13 Don‚Äôt just do pilots that automate old processes. Rather, launch major reengineering efforts across all processes.

8/13 Hire or promote a real leader from within, and give them the title of ‚ÄúBlockchain Czar".
9/13 Buy a Bitcoin Exchange. One of the big banks will blink first & buy one of the 50 Bitcoin exchanges and delight their customers.
10/13 When every asset has a blockchain linkage, it puts it at par with bits that travel at Internet speeds.
11/13 The blockchain is not perfect, but it is a perfect catalyst for reengineering, and this opportunity doesn‚Äôt present itself that often.
12/13 Banks can go slow and be left behind, or they can go deep and leapfrog.
